  "text": "T. Honda et al. Environmental Research 164 (2018) 1-8 pathway by which air pollution is hypothesized to exert cardiovascular health effects, has also been related to increased aortic arterial stiffness [CITATION_1] . We observed borderline significant effect modification by diabetes status. Interestingly, diabetes has also been shown to accelerate ageassociated increases in conduit artery stiffness which may help mechanistically explain the observed effect modification [CITATION_2] . Importantly, concomitant hypertension has been estimated to account for up to 75% of cardiovascular disease among diabetics [CITATION_3] . As diabetics are already at increased risk of cardiovascular events as compared to non-diabetics (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention CDC, 2014), the observed increased risk of blood pressure elevations among diabetics may thus be of significant clinical import. Specifically, it may demonstrate that diabetics are a particularly susceptible population to the increased cardiovascular risk consistently associated with air pollution.",
